[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In computer programming, an **anonymous function** (**function literal**, **lambda function**, or **block**) is a function definition that is not bound to an identifier.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions are often arguments being passed to higher-order functions or used for constructing the result of a higher-order function that needs to return a function.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] If the function is only used once, or a limited number of times, an anonymous function may be syntactically lighter than using a named function.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions are ubiquitous in functional programming languages and other languages with first-class functions, where they fulfil the same role for the function type as literals do for other data types.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions originate in the work of Alonzo Church in his invention of the lambda calculus, in which all functions are anonymous, in 1936, before electronic computers.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In several programming languages, anonymous functions are introduced using the keyword *lambda*, and anonymous functions are often referred to as **lambdas** or **lambda abstractions**.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions have been a feature of programming languages since Lisp in 1958, and a growing number of modern programming languages support anonymous functions.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The names "lambda abstraction", "lambda function", and "lambda expression" refer to the notation of function abstraction in lambda calculus, where the usual function $f(x)=M$ would be written $(\lambda x.M)$ , and where M is an expression that uses x .
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Compare to the Python syntax of `lambda x: M`.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The name "arrow function" refers to the mathematical "maps to" symbol, $x\mapsto M$ .
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Compare to the JavaScript syntax of `x => M`.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions can encapsulate functionality that does not require naming and is intended for short-term or localized use.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Some notable examples include closures and currying.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The use of anonymous functions is a matter of style.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Using them is never the only way to solve a problem; each anonymous function could instead be defined as a named function and called by name.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions often provide a briefer notation than defining named functions.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In languages that do not permit the definition of named functions in local scopes, anonymous functions may provide encapsulation via localized scope, however the code in the body of such anonymous function may not be re-usable, or amenable to separate testing.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Short/simple anonymous functions used in expressions may be easier to read and understand than separately defined named functions, though lacking a descriptive name may reduce code readability.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The following examples are written in Python 3.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Many languages provide a generic function that sorts a list (or array) of objects into an order determined by a comparison function which compares two objects to determine if they are equal or if one is greater or less than the other.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Using an anonymous comparison function expression passed as an argument to a generic sort function is often more concise than creating a named comparison function.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The anonymous function accepts one argument, `x`, and returns the length of its argument, which is then used by the `sort()` method as the criteria for sorting.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The expression returned by the lambda function can be assigned to a variable and used in the code at multiple places.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Note that `11.2` has class name "`float`", `10` has class name "`int`", and `'number'` has class name "`str`".
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Closures are functions evaluated in an environment containing bound variables.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The following example binds the variable "threshold" within an anonymous function that compares input values to this threshold.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] It would be impractical to create a function for every possible comparison function and may be too inconvenient to keep the threshold around for further use.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Regardless of the reason why a closure is used, the anonymous function is the entity that contains the functionality that does the comparing.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Currying transforms a function that takes multiple arguments into a sequence of functions each accepting a single argument.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In this example, a function that performs division by any integer is transformed into one that performs division by a set integer.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] While the use of anonymous functions is perhaps not common with currying, it still can be used.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In the above example, the function divisor generates functions with a specified divisor.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The functions half and third curry the divide function with a fixed divisor.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The divisor function also forms a closure by binding the variable `d`.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] A higher-order function is a function that takes a function as an argument or returns one as a result.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] This technique is frequently employed to tailor the behavior of a generically defined function, such as a loop or recursion pattern.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Anonymous functions are a convenient way to specify such function arguments.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The map function performs a function call on each element of a list.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The following example squares every element in an array with an anonymous function.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The anonymous function takes an argument and returns its square.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The filter function returns all elements from a list that evaluate True when passed to a certain function.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The anonymous function checks if the argument passed to it is even.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] A fold function runs over all elements in a structure (for lists usually left-to-right, a "left fold", called `reduce` in Python), accumulating a value as it goes.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The anonymous function here is the multiplication of the two arguments.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] A fold does not necessarily produce a single scalar value; it can also generate structured results such as lists.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Instead, both map and filter can be created using fold.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In map, the value that is accumulated is a new list, containing the results of applying a function to each element of the original list.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] In filter, the value that is accumulated is a new list containing only those elements that match the given condition.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The following is a list of programming languages that support unnamed anonymous functions fully, or partly as some variant, or not at all.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] The following table illustrates several common patterns.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Notably, languages like C, Pascal, and Object Pascal—which traditionally do not support anonymous functions—are all statically typed languages.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] However, statically typed languages can support anonymous functions.
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] For example, the ML languages are statically typed and fundamentally include anonymous functions, and Delphi, a dialect of Object Pascal, has been extended to support anonymous functions, as has C++ (by the C++11 standard).
[src:aws-lambda/anonymous-function] Second, the languages that treat functions as first-class functions (Dylan, Haskell, JavaScript, Lisp, ML, Perl, Python, Ruby, Scheme) generally have anonymous function support so that functions can be defined and passed around as easily as other data types.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Each AWS Lambda instance runs within a lightweight, isolated environment powered by Firecracker microVMs.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] These microVMs are initialized with a runtime environment based on Amazon Linux (Amazon Linux AMI or Amazon Linux 2).
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Firecracker provides hardware-virtualization-based isolation, aiming to achieve near-bare-metal performance with minimal overhead.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] AWS claims that, unlike traditional virtual machines, these microVMs launch in milliseconds, enabling rapid and secure function execution with a minimal memory footprint.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] The Amazon Linux AMI is specifically optimized for cloud-native and serverless workloads, aiming to provide a lightweight, secure, and performant runtime environment.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] As of 2025, AWS Lambda supports Node.js, Python, Java, Go, .NET, Ruby and custom runtimes.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Rust and Go generally exhibit lower cold start times in AWS Lambda compared to Java and C# because they compile to native static binaries, eliminating the need for a virtual machine (JVM or .NET CLR) and reducing runtime initialization overhead.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Go has some minimal runtime initialization, including garbage collection and goroutine management, but its impact on cold start time is relatively low.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Rust, which is fully ahead-of-time (AOT) compiled and does not require a runtime, often achieves the lowest cold start latency among supported languages.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Java and C# run on managed runtime environments, introducing additional cold start latency due to runtime initialization and Just-In-Time (JIT) compilation.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, modern optimizations have mitigated some of these challenges. .NET 7 and .NET 8 support Ahead-of-Time (AOT) compilation, reducing cold start times by precompiling code.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Additionally, AWS Lambda SnapStart for Java 11 and 17 pre-warms and snapshots execution state, significantly decreasing cold start overhead for Java-based functions.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Despite these optimizations, Rust and Go typically maintain lower cold start times due to their minimal runtime dependencies.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] In long-running workloads, JIT compilation in Java and .NET may improve execution speed through dynamic optimizations.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, this benefit is workload-dependent, and Rust's AOT compilation often provides better performance consistency, particularly for CPU-bound tasks.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] For short-lived Lambda invocations, Rust and Go generally maintain more predictable performance, as JIT optimizations may not have sufficient time to take effect.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Historically, Rust and Go required additional effort in deployment due to cross-compilation and static linking challenges.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Rust, in particular, often necessitates MUSL-based static linking for AWS Lambda compatibility.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, advancements in deployment tooling, including AWS Serverless Application Model (AWS SAM), GitHub Actions, and Lambda container images, have simplified this process.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Go benefits from native static linking support, making its deployment process comparatively straightforward.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] AWS Lambda's support for container images further reduces runtime compatibility concerns, enabling the use of custom runtimes and dependencies.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Reserved Concurrency sets a maximum number of concurrent executions for a specific function and reserves that capacity from the account's overall concurrency limit.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, it does not keep execution environments initialized or guarantee that any instances remain running when the function is idle.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Provisioned Concurrency, in contrast, maintains a specified number of pre-initialized execution environments, ensuring that the function does not experience cold starts and does not scale down to zero.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] The Lambda Function URL gives Lambda a unique and permanent URL which can be accessed by authenticated and non-authenticated users alike.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] AWS Lambda layer is a ZIP archive containing libraries, frameworks or custom code that can be added to AWS Lambda functions.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Migration from AWS Lambda to other AWS compute services, such as Amazon ECS, presents challenges due to tight integration with AWS Lambda's APIs, often referred to as service lock-in.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Tools like AWS Lambda Web Adapter offer a pathway for portability by enabling developers to build web applications using familiar frameworks under a monolithic Lambda design pattern.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, this approach introduces limitations, including coarser-grained alerting and access controls, potential cold start delays with large dependencies, and limited suitability for non-HTTP APIs.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] AWS Lambda Powertools is an open-source library developed by AWS that provides utilities for AWS Lambda functions.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] The core utilities includes structured logging, metrics and tracing.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] It also offers other utilities for common use cases when developing AWS Lambda functions.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] As of March 2025, it also includes data masking support for Python.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] As of March 2025, AWS Lambda supports limited vertical scaling by increasing the number of virtual central processing units (vCPUs) through memory allocation.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, it does not allow an increase in single-thread performance, as clock speed remains fixed.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] When a function is allocated only one vCPU, multiple threads share the same core, resulting in context switching rather than true parallel execution.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] As a result, multi-threading in single-vCPU environments is primarily beneficial for input/output (I/O)-bound workloads rather than computationally intensive tasks.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] Allocating additional memory in AWS Lambda enables multiple vCPUs, allowing for parallel execution.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] However, the clock speed per core remains unchanged, limiting individual thread performance.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] This configuration makes AWS Lambda suitable for workloads that scale horizontally or leverage parallelism but less optimal for applications that require high single-thread performance.
[src:aws-lambda/aws-lambda] In April 2022, researchers found cryptomining malware targeting AWS Lambda named "Denonia".
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:aws-lambda/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Function as a Service is a subset of the serverless computing ecosystem.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] The "Grain of Sand Anti-pattern" refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] "Lambda Pinball" is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Function as a service workloads may encounter migration obstacles due to service lock-in from tight vendor integrations.
[src:aws-lambda/function-as-a-service] Hexagonal architecture can facilitate workload portability.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:aws-lambda/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
